<?xml-stylesheet type="text/xsl" href="../assets/xml/rss.xsl" media="all"?><rss xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom" version="2.0" xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/"><channel><title>Blog-O! (Posts about smime)</title><link>https://bwinton.github.io/weblog.latte.ca/</link><description></description><atom:link rel="self" href="https://bwinton.github.io/weblog.latte.ca/tags/smime.xml" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><language>en</language><lastBuildDate>Sat, 13 Apr 2019 21:03:21 GMT</lastBuildDate><generator>Nikola (getnikola.com)</generator><docs>http://blogs.law.harvard.edu/tech/rss</docs><item><title>More secure!</title><link>https://bwinton.github.io/weblog.latte.ca/blake/tech/thunderbird/moresecure/</link><dc:creator>Blake Winton</dc:creator><description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;p&gt;As someone who works on an email client, I’m interested in making
my communications more secure.  So, with the assistance of
&lt;a href="http://perso.hirlimann.net/~ludo/blog/"&gt;Ludovic&lt;/a&gt; and
&lt;a href="http://gozer.ectoplasm.org/blog/"&gt;Gozer&lt;/a&gt;, I got a client certificate that
would allow me to sign and encrypt my messages.  (Check out the envelope
and lock in the image below.)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt="An outgoing message, with an envelope and a
lock" src="https://bwinton.github.io/weblog.latte.ca/images/blake/SignedAndEncrypted.png" title="Signed and Encrypted"&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Most of the time, I’ll probably just sign my messages – after all, that’s
what I’ve set it up to do by default – but it’s nice to know that if
there’s something I need to encrypt, that option is now available to me.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description><category>mozilla</category><category>smime</category><category>thunderbird</category><guid>https://bwinton.github.io/weblog.latte.ca/blake/tech/thunderbird/moresecure/</guid><pubDate>Wed, 25 Aug 2010 21:34:42 GMT</pubDate></item></channel></rss>